I'll start by executing the file_operations_reader tool to read the input data as the first step in our pipeline.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll proceed with the next step in the pipeline - filtering the data. I'll use the data_processing_filter tool to process the output from the previous step.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "filter_rules": {
      "default": "include_all"
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>

            Next, I'll validate the data using the data_processing_validator tool. According to the workflow plan, this requires the data_processing_parser tool first, so I'll execute that first.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that the parser has executed successfully, I'll proceed with the data validation step using the data_processing_validator tool.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "validation_rules": {
      "default": "basic_schema_check"
    }
  }
}
</tool_call>

                        I'll now proceed with the final transformation step using the data_processing_transformer tool to complete the pipeline.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "transformation": "default_format_conversion",
    "output_format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>
